<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>I find more the opposite; RL chat is used for fluffy taking-a-break type stuff (take off a few minutes to go the coffee machine and talk about your weekend), while real work starts once everyone gets back to their desk and puts on headphones, using IRC or IM as a unobtrusive backchannel to discuss the stuff we're working on. Works nicely with collaborative document writing in Google Docs as well.<p>I've tried an "everyone in the same room" approach to collaborative document writing a few times, and that was a disaster for &#62;2 people; online just works much better. Though IRL can sometimes work if it's exactly two people collaborating, who work well together, sharing one keyboard in the style of Extreme Programming (whether on code or prose).</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=200></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3412468 href="vote?for=3412468&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%67%32%63%4c%74%32%37%4d%7a%6e"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3412468></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=defrost">defrost</a> 35 days ago  | <a href="item?id=3412468">link</a></span></div><br>
